A '''B'''iological '''I'''ndicator '''E'''valuation '''R'''esistometer or BIER vessel is a piece of equipment used to determine the time taken to reduce a bioload by 90% (also known as a log 1 reduction).  The name derives from how the equipment is used.  A BIER vessel evaluates the resistance of biological indicators to moist heat (steam) sterilization.  For example, if a 90% reduction is determined to be 5 minutes for the microorganism being evaluated, then a [[D-value (microbiology)|D-value]] of 5 is assigned. D values are specific to starting bioload, substrate (the material the spores are on) and microbe species.
BIER vessels typically cost in excess of $100 000US and therefore tend to be located where biological indicators are manufactured.

