[[File:Jack Delano, Tap dancing class at Iowa State College, 1942.jpg|thumb|Tap dancing class, 1942.]]
'''Dance education''' is the transferring of [[dance]] performance skills and knowledge of dance to [[students]] through teaching and [[training]], or acquiring such knowledge and skills through [[research]].

==Curriculum==
In general, a dance education [[curriculum]] is designed to impart dance performance skills, or knowledge of dance, or both to students. Knowledge-oriented curricula may cover any of a diverse range of topics, including [[dance notation]], [[human anatomy]], [[physics]], [[dance history]], and cultural aspects of dance.{{cn|date=May 2017}}

A curriculum may involve the study of one or more dance genres, including formal genres such as [[ballet]], [[ballroom dancing|ballroom]], [[contemporary dance|contemporary]], [[jazz dance|jazz]], [[Latin dancing|Latin]], and [[tap dance|tap]] dance, and informal and social genres such as [[line dancing|line]], [[freestyle dance|freestyle]], and [[sequence dancing|sequence]] dancing.{{cn|date=May 2017}}

==Professional dance education==
Professional and [[vocational education|vocational]] dance education is offered by both public and private institutions. Private institutions, which are commonly known as dance schools or dance colleges, are typically focused on dance education, whereas public institutions usually cover a broad range of topics. Examples of private institutions include the [[Royal Ballet School]] and the [[School of American Ballet]].

Many public and private universities and colleges offer minor programs in dance, or major programs with academic degrees such as [[Bachelor of Arts]], [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]], and [[Master of Fine Arts]] in dance. Some public [[secondary education]] institutions offer comprehensive dance education curricula. For example, [[Jefferson High School (Portland, Oregon)]] offers concentrated vocational dance education in conjunction with its pre-professional dance company, [[The Jefferson Dancers]].

